# P0 fix: experiment outputs are NOT source — they are reproducible
# artifacts regenerated by `python run_all.py` (or the individual
# `run_*.py` scripts). Committing them to git had two problems:
#   1. Every re-run with even slightly different random seeds / torch
#      versions produced a multi-MB JSON/PDF diff that polluted the
#      commit history and made `git blame` nearly useless on adjacent
#      source files.
#   2. The committed JSONs were often stale relative to the latest
#      source code (a contributor forgets to re-run after editing an
#      op), giving readers misleading "this is the current behaviour"
#      impressions.
# CI / Kaggle runs should produce these as artifacts (uploaded as build
# outputs, not committed). The committed historical results have been
# removed via `git rm --cached`; the files remain on disk locally for
# one-time reference but are no longer tracked.
# To view results without re-running, check out an earlier commit before
# this .gitignore entry was added.
results/
figures/

# P1 fix: lock the Python environment to a known-good range. The
# committed `requirements.txt` and `pyproject.toml` pin upper bounds
# (e.g. torch>=2.2,<2.7) so a fresh `pip install -e .` does not pull a
# breaking torch release (e.g. SDPA behaviour changes between 2.3 and
# 2.6 that affect the softmax baseline). The lock file itself is not
# committed because the project has no CI matrix that exercises every
# combination; the bounded range is the practical compromise.
*.lock
poetry.lock
uv.lock

.opencode/
